Question 1a

y <- c(2, 5, 4.3, 4.2, 8) # Observed data 
 
compute.mse <- Vectorize(function(b0) { 
  return(mean((y - b0) ** 2)) 
}) 
 
b0 <- seq(0, 10, length.out = 10000 + 1) # Try various b0's 
mse <- compute.mse(b0) 
plot(b0, mse,
     col = "blue", 
     lwd = 1,  
     main = "b0 vs mse",
     xlab = "b0",
     ylab = "mse"
     ) # Plot b0 vs mse 

mse[which.min(mse)]
## [1] 3.736
b0[which.min(mse)]
## [1] 4.7
mean(y)
## [1] 4.7
cat("The minimum MSE value is", mse[which.min(mse)], "\n")
## The minimum MSE value is 3.736
cat("b0 is", b0[which.min(mse)], "to attains this minimum", "\n")
## b0 is 4.7 to attains this minimum
cat("mean(y) is", mean(y), "\n")
## mean(y) is 4.7
cat("This optimal b0 value equals mean(y)", "\n")
## This optimal b0 value equals mean(y)

Question 2a

y <- c(2, 5, 4.3, 4.2, 8) # Observed data 
 
compute.mae <- Vectorize(function(b0) { 
  return(mean(abs(y - b0))) 
}) 
 
b0 <- seq(0, 10, length.out = 10000 + 1) # Try various b0's 
mae <- compute.mae(b0) 
plot(b0, mae,
     col = "green", 
     lwd = 1,  
     main = "b0 vs mae",
     xlab = "b0",
     ylab = "mae"
     ) # Plot b0 vs mae 

cat("It is a V shape. y values are located on the 2 wings of the V shape. The 2 wings meet at the bottom of the V shape, which is the min value of mae. The MSE and MAE are averaged forms of the L2 norm and L1 norm. b0 vs mae line is not as smooth as b0 vs mse line.", "\n")
## It is a V shape. y values are located on the 2 wings of the V shape. The 2 wings meet at the bottom of the V shape, which is the min value of mae. The MSE and MAE are averaged forms of the L2 norm and L1 norm. b0 vs mae line is not as smooth as b0 vs mse line.

Question 2b

mae[which.min(mae)]
## [1] 1.36
b0[which.min(mae)]
## [1] 4.3
mean(y)
## [1] 4.7
median(y)
## [1] 4.3
summary(y)
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##     2.0     4.2     4.3     4.7     5.0     8.0
cat("The minimum MAE value is", mae[which.min(mae)], "\n")
## The minimum MAE value is 1.36
cat("b0 is", b0[which.min(mae)], "to attains this minimum", "\n")
## b0 is 4.3 to attains this minimum
cat("This optimal b0 value is less than mean(y). In this case, this optimal b0 value is equal to median(y). ", "\n")
## This optimal b0 value is less than mean(y). In this case, this optimal b0 value is equal to median(y).
cat("MAE takes the absolute value of the differences between predicted and actual values. It makes MAE inherently robust to outliers. Unlike MSE, MAE treats all errors equally, minimizing the impact of outliers on the loss function.")
## MAE takes the absolute value of the differences between predicted and actual values. It makes MAE inherently robust to outliers. Unlike MSE, MAE treats all errors equally, minimizing the impact of outliers on the loss function.

Question 3a

data <- read.csv('chicago_taxi_trip_sample.csv')
dim(data)
## [1] 100000     17
cat("Fit a linear regression model with trip_total as the response variable and trip_miles as the explanatory variable.")
## Fit a linear regression model with trip_total as the response variable and trip_miles as the explanatory variable.
model <- lm(trip_total ~ trip_miles, data = data)
summary(model)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = trip_total ~ trip_miles, data = data)
## 
## Residuals:
##      Min       1Q   Median       3Q      Max 
## -194.732   -4.304   -1.773    1.408  142.854 
## 
## Coefficients:
##             Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)    
## (Intercept) 8.190563   0.036165   226.5   <2e-16 ***
## trip_miles  2.563752   0.004092   626.5   <2e-16 ***
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## Residual standard error: 8.249 on 99998 degrees of freedom
## Multiple R-squared:  0.797,  Adjusted R-squared:  0.797 
## F-statistic: 3.925e+05 on 1 and 99998 DF,  p-value: < 2.2e-16
cat("The fitted intercept 𝛽0∗ and slope 𝛽1∗ parameters are")
## The fitted intercept 𝛽0∗ and slope 𝛽1∗ parameters are
coef(model)
## (Intercept)  trip_miles 
##    8.190563    2.563752
cat("The fitted model equation is y = ", coef(model)[1], " + ", coef(model)[2], "x", "\n")
## The fitted model equation is y =  8.190563  +  2.563752 x
# Compute mean squared error MSE
y <- data$trip_total
y.pred <- fitted(model) # Also fitted.values(model) and model$fitted.values
mean((y - y.pred) ** 2)
## [1] 68.04876
cat("MSE of the fitted model on the observed data is", mean((y - y.pred) ** 2), "\n")
## MSE of the fitted model on the observed data is 68.04876
cat("The R^2 value for the fitted model is", summary(model)$r.squared, "\n")
## The R^2 value for the fitted model is 0.796969
cor(y, y.pred)
## [1] 0.8927312
cor(y, y.pred) ** 2
## [1] 0.796969
cat("The sqaured value of cor(y, y.pred) is equal to R^2", "\n")
## The sqaured value of cor(y, y.pred) is equal to R^2
z <- 8.190563 + 2.563752*10
cat("The predicted cost for a 10 miles trip is", z)
## The predicted cost for a 10 miles trip is 33.82808

Question 3b

data$trip_km <- data$trip_miles * 1.609 
model <- lm(trip_total ~ trip_km, data = data) 
cat("The fitted intercept 𝛽0∗ and slope 𝛽1∗ parameters are")
## The fitted intercept 𝛽0∗ and slope 𝛽1∗ parameters are
coef(model)
## (Intercept)     trip_km 
##    8.190563    1.593382
cat("It follows affine transformation. x -> 1.609 x. 𝛽0 does not change, 𝛽1 becomes (1/1.609)*2.563752 = 1.593382. 2.563752 is the beta in 3a.", "\n")
## It follows affine transformation. x -> 1.609 x. 𝛽0 does not change, 𝛽1 becomes (1/1.609)*2.563752 = 1.593382. 2.563752 is the beta in 3a.
zkm <- 8.190563 + 1.593382*16.09
cat("The predicted cost for a 16.09 km trip is", zkm, ". It is same prediction as 3a. Affine transformation does not change y.pred value.")
## The predicted cost for a 16.09 km trip is 33.82808 . It is same prediction as 3a. Affine transformation does not change y.pred value.

Question 3c

cat("Fit a linear regression model with trip_miles and tolls as explanatory variables.  What is the 𝑅^2 value for this fitted model?", "\n")
## Fit a linear regression model with trip_miles and tolls as explanatory variables.  What is the 𝑅^2 value for this fitted model?
summary(lm(trip_total ~ trip_miles + tolls, data = data))$r.squared
## [1] 0.7970199
cat("Fit a linear regression model with trip_miles and extras as explanatory variables.  What is the 𝑅^2 value for this fitted model?", "\n")
## Fit a linear regression model with trip_miles and extras as explanatory variables.  What is the 𝑅^2 value for this fitted model?
summary(lm(trip_total ~ trip_miles + extras, data = data))$r.squared
## [1] 0.8381408
cat("Based on goodness-of-fit via 𝑅^2, extras is a more useful explanatory variable.", "\n")
## Based on goodness-of-fit via 𝑅^2, extras is a more useful explanatory variable.
cat("Fit a linear regression model with trip_miles, tolls , and extras as explanatory variables.  What is the 𝑅^2 value for this fitted model?", "\n")
## Fit a linear regression model with trip_miles, tolls , and extras as explanatory variables.  What is the 𝑅^2 value for this fitted model?
summary(lm(trip_total ~ trip_miles + tolls + extras, data = data))$r.squared
## [1] 0.8382525
cat("This R^2 is only a little bit higher than previous models.")
## This R^2 is only a little bit higher than previous models.
